WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:17.160
So pins provides a way to easily share things, either across projects or across people. What

00:00:17.160 --> 00:00:24.879
ends up happening oftentimes in data science work? We have some asset, and maybe it's data

00:00:24.879 --> 00:00:35.639
or it's a model or some other R object. And we either need to reuse this asset later on

00:00:35.639 --> 00:00:40.959
downstream or across different projects, or we might need to share it with different members

00:00:40.959 --> 00:00:48.799
of our team. We say anything that can be serializable in R. So think about how you might stick something

00:00:48.799 --> 00:00:54.560
on a corkboard so you can keep it handy, right? Or you'd stick a flyer on a community bulletin

00:00:54.560 --> 00:01:01.360
board at the grocery store, right? So that other people can see it. And so the pins package pins

00:01:01.360 --> 00:01:08.720
objects to what's called a board. This is analogous to this corkboard idea. And so this board is this

00:01:08.720 --> 00:01:15.199
place where files are written and they're read from. Examples of boards are things like you can

00:01:15.199 --> 00:01:23.680
have a board that's S3 storage, shared folders like network drives or Dropbox. You can have

00:01:23.680 --> 00:01:31.040
your RStudio Connect be a board, a SharePoint site be a board. Really, it's just a file store,

00:01:31.040 --> 00:01:36.400
a file share. Nothing magical about that. It's just pins has a nomenclature and a way of organizing

00:01:36.400 --> 00:01:41.440
things in this place on the board so that you can interact with them through the package.

00:01:42.400 --> 00:01:47.680
Okay. So what I'm hearing is I can pin all kinds of things in all kinds of locations.

00:01:48.400 --> 00:01:48.900
Yes.

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:59.440
It works nicely with Connect, but there's nothing specifically implemented in pins

00:02:00.160 --> 00:02:08.080
for Connect. They're the things that Connect does to make life for pins a little bit better.

00:02:09.279 --> 00:02:15.759
Connect will give you access to the same sharing content sharing settings that you have for any

00:02:15.759 --> 00:02:20.399
piece of content on Connect. So I can put my pin on Connect and I can specify who

00:02:21.039 --> 00:02:29.440
should be able to access it and share it. And then pins does have a nice preview

00:02:29.440 --> 00:02:37.520
of the pinned object. I like that feature, but that's a Connect implementation

00:02:37.520 --> 00:02:40.800
for how it reads pins, nothing specific in the pins package itself.

00:02:41.039 --> 00:02:53.360
So if I work by myself, either for whatever reason, I am a team of one, how might I use pins?

00:02:53.360 --> 00:03:02.800
A lot comes down to what are your pain points and what do you have available to you already

00:03:03.360 --> 00:03:08.160
for storing data, sharing data, accessing data downstream, things like that.

00:03:08.800 --> 00:03:16.399
Right. So do you, in your team of one, do you need to reuse something in other work?

00:03:16.960 --> 00:03:22.880
Right. Do you have like a reference table or, you know, some kind of other information

00:03:22.880 --> 00:03:26.559
that multiple projects are going to use? You might need to come back to this.

00:03:27.199 --> 00:03:34.000
Pins could be a pretty good use case for that. Right. Or, you know, do you just not have a

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:40.080
convenient place to put things? You know, pins comes in and gets to be really helpful

00:03:40.720 --> 00:03:48.399
when you just maybe don't have another place to store data. Sometimes, you know, teams that don't

00:03:48.399 --> 00:03:53.759
have ready access to a database, you know, find pins to be pretty helpful because it kind of

00:03:53.759 --> 00:03:59.039
makes them self-sufficient. They can be more autonomous in this way. You don't have the

00:03:59.039 --> 00:04:02.880
